Sample workflow
---------------
Generate all sample lists from `datasets.mk`
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples-lists

Build all sample ROOT files from `datasets.mk`
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples

Render the richer sample catalog into generated make/manifest files
  bash tools/render-sample-catalog.sh

Build all sample ROOT files from the generated sample catalog
  make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk samples

Build all logical dataset ROOT files from the generated sample catalog
  make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk datasets

Print all managed sample outputs
  make -f samples-dag.mk print-samples

Print all managed dataset outputs
  make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk print-datasets

Remove generated sample ROOT files and sample lists
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples-clean

Generate one sample list directly
  tools/mklist.sh --dir /path/to/input --pat "nu_selection.root,nu_selection_data.root" --out samplelists/example.list
  tools/mklist.sh --list samplelists/existing.list --out samplelists/example.list
  tools/mklist.sh --samdef nl_run1_fhc_detvar_sce_goodruns --out samplelists/run1_fhc/beam-sce.list

Build one logical sample ROOT file from an explicit shard manifest
  build/bin/mk_sample \
    --sample beam \
    --manifest beam.sample.manifest \
    output.root overlay nominal numi fhc

Manifest row format
  shard sample-list-path

Build one legacy single-list sample ROOT file directly
  build/bin/mk_sample output.root input.list data nominal numi fhc

Dataset workflow
----------------
Build one persistent DatasetIO file directly in the legacy keyed mode
  build/bin/mk_dataset output.dataset.root context sample-key=sample.root

Build a DatasetIO file and stamp sample definitions
  build/bin/mk_dataset --defs sample.defs output.dataset.root run1-numi-fhc beam-s0=build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root

Build one logical DatasetIO file from an explicit scope plus manifest
  build/bin/mk_dataset \
    --defs samples/generated/run1_fhc.sample.defs \
    --campaign run1_fhc_v08_00_00_82 \
    --run run1 \
    --beam numi \
    --polarity fhc \
    --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.dataset.manifest \
    build/datasets/run1_fhc.root

Dataset manifest row format
  sample sample-root-path

The plain text `sample.defs` format is:
  key variation nominal tag role defname [campaign]

Use `-` for an empty field.

Event-list workflow
-------------------
Build one persistent EventListIO file directly
  build/bin/mk_eventlist output.eventlist.root input.dataset.root

Build one persistent EventListIO file with explicit tree names and selection
  build/bin/mk_eventlist --event-tree EventSelectionFilter --subrun-tree SubRun --selection "selected != 0" output.eventlist.root input.dataset.root

Distribution workflow
---------------------
Build one DistributionIO cache file directly from an EventListIO input
  build/bin/mk_dist \
    --selection "__pass_muon__" \
    --detvars beam-s0-sce,beam-s0-wiremodx \
    --fine-nbins 400 \
    --genie \
    output.dists.root \
    output.eventlist.root \
    beam-s0 \
    topological_score \
    50 0 1

Build one canonical two-lane systematics cache:
  detector variations from alternate samples plus reweighting families from the
  nominal sample
  build/bin/mk_dist \
    --selection "__pass_muon__" \
    --detvars beam-s0-sce,beam-s0-wiremodx \
    --fine-nbins 400 \
    --genie \
    --flux \
    --reint \
    build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
    build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
    beam-s0 \
    topological_score \
    50 0 1

Notes:
  `mk_eventlist` resolves `__w_norm__` from the embedded DatasetIO run/subrun
  normalization surface, `__w_cv__` from the central-value event-weight
  branches, and persists `__w__ = __w_norm__ * __w_cv__` plus `__w2__`.
  `mk_dist` is the preferred one-request DistributionIO cache builder.
  `--detvars` drives the detector lane from alternate EventListIO samples.
  `--genie`, `--flux`, and `--reint` drive the reweighting
  lane from branches on the nominal sample.
  `--no-overwrite` keeps existing matching cache entries instead of
  rebuilding them.

Fit workflow
------------
Run one native xsec fit directly from cached DistributionIO inputs and print
the fit report
  cat > muon_region.fit.manifest <<'EOF'
  signal signal beam-s0
  beam_bkg background beam-bkg
  ext background ext
  dirt background dirt
  obs data beam-data
  EOF
  build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
    --manifest muon_region.fit.manifest \
    output.dists.root \
    muon_region

Run one quick two-process fit with explicit observed bins
  build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
    --signal-process signal \
    --data-bins "12,10,9,7,6,5,4,3,2,1" \
    output.dists.root \
    beam-s0 \
    beam-bkg \
    muon_region

If the fit intentionally carries an all-zero observed spectrum
  build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
    --allow-zero-data \
    output.dists.root \
    beam-s0 \
    beam-bkg \
    muon_region

Run one native xsec fit with explicit signal process and write a text report
  build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
    --signal-process signal \
    --output muon_region.fit.txt \
    --manifest muon_region.fit.manifest \
    output.dists.root \
    muon_region

Notes:
  `mk_xsec_fit` now consumes cached `DistributionIO` entries directly.
  Manifest rows use the format:
    `process-name kind sample-key [cache-key]`
  `data` rows fill the observed bins automatically.
  Without manifest data rows, pass `--data-bins` or opt into an intentional
  empty observation with `--allow-zero-data`.

Macro runner
------------
Run one ROOT macro through the common wrapper
  bash tools/run-macro plot_event_display build/eventlists/run1.root beam-s0 0 U detector
  bash tools/run-macro plot_efficiency build/eventlists/run1.root topological_score "selected != 0" "__pass_muon__" 50 0 1 beam-s0
  bash tools/run-macro inspect_dist output.dists.root beam-s0

Notes
-----
`tools/run-macro`
  Uses simple literal inference with optional prefixes instead of scraping the
  macro signature at runtime. Use `s:<text>` when a string value would
  otherwise look numeric.

`mk_sample`
  Accepts an optional `--run-db PATH`. If omitted, it checks
  `AMARANTIN_RUN_DB` and otherwise falls back to:
    /exp/uboone/data/uboonebeam/beamdb/run.db
  The native logical-sample form is:
    `--sample NAME --manifest SAMPLE.manifest output.root ...`
  The older positional `output.root input.list ...` form is still available as
  a transitional bridge. If you still need a file containing many list paths,
  pass it as `@path`.

`samples-dag.mk`
  Uses `build/bin/mk_sample` as its canonical producer and records small stamp
  files to avoid rebuilding unchanged sample outputs. It now also accepts
  generated logical-sample manifests through `logical_samples.<dataset>`,
  `sample_manifest.<dataset>.<logical>`, and
  `sample_artifacts.<dataset>.<logical>`.
  Per-artifact list generation still uses generated variables such as
  `sample_source_kind.<dataset>.<artifact>`,
  `sample_source_ref.<dataset>.<artifact>`,
  `sample_origin.<dataset>.<logical>` and
  `sample_variation.<dataset>.<logical>`.

`mk_dataset --defs`
  Is the preferred place to stamp workflow metadata like `nominal`, `tag`,
  `role`, `defname`, and `campaign`.

`mk_dataset --manifest`
  In the native scope mode, consumes already-logical sample roots and rejects
  duplicate sample rows. The older repeated-key merge behavior remains
  available only through the legacy context-string path.

`mk_dist`, `mk_xsec_fit`
  Are the preferred scripted cache / fit entrypoints.
  Older helper macros such as `cache_systematics.C`, `write_channel.C`,
  `fit_channel.C`, and `scan_mu.C` may remain useful for ad hoc ROOT
  sessions, but they are no longer the documented workflow.

Generated `samples/generated/datasets.mk`
  Also carries `dataset_defs.<dataset>`, `dataset_manifest.<dataset>`,
  `dataset_run.<dataset>`, `dataset_beam.<dataset>`,
  `dataset_polarity.<dataset>`, optional `dataset_campaign.<dataset>`, and one
  `sample_manifest.<dataset>.<logical>` entry per logical sample so
  `make -f samples-dag.mk ... samples` builds logical `SampleIO` roots directly
  and `... datasets` assembles logical datasets from those roots.
